WEBVTT

00:03.670 --> 00:05.210
Meredith: The first surgeons
were vivisectionists.

00:05.210 --> 00:06.750
♪ Yeah ♪
When they opened a body,

00:06.750 --> 00:08.290
they had no intention
of closing it.

00:08.290 --> 00:09.830
♪ One, two, three, yeah ♪

00:09.830 --> 00:12.830
[ Both breathing heavily ]

00:12.830 --> 00:14.880
They just wanted to see
what was inside.

00:14.880 --> 00:16.290
Phenomenal job.

00:16.290 --> 00:17.670
Yeah.

00:17.670 --> 00:19.880
Hats off to you, too.

00:19.880 --> 00:23.120
And what they found was
a world of possibility...

00:23.120 --> 00:25.460
You know, this
no-strings-attached thing --

00:25.460 --> 00:27.420
it is like
hidden treasure.

00:27.420 --> 00:30.750
All of the fun,
none of the emotional baggage.

00:30.750 --> 00:32.380
We should write a book.

00:32.380 --> 00:34.580
We would make millions.
[ Laughs ]

00:34.580 --> 00:36.250
Mmm, mmm, mmm. Oh.
[ Watch vibrates ]

00:36.250 --> 00:38.580
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh, ooh, ooh ♪

00:38.580 --> 00:39.880
Oh, shoot.

00:39.880 --> 00:41.710
[ Sighs ]
I gotta go.

00:41.710 --> 00:43.120
♪ Give 'em what they want ♪

00:43.120 --> 00:45.420
It's Intern
Trauma Certification Day today.

00:45.420 --> 00:47.000
Okay.

00:47.000 --> 00:49.290
...the possibility to heal...

00:49.290 --> 00:50.420
[ Exhales heavily ]

00:50.420 --> 00:51.790
...to reverse the damage...

00:51.790 --> 00:53.500
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

00:53.500 --> 00:55.000
...to turn back time.

00:55.000 --> 00:56.500
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪
You sure this is cool?

00:56.500 --> 00:58.750
You know,
me leaving in a hurry?

00:58.750 --> 01:00.170
I just --
I don't want to be a --

01:00.170 --> 01:01.920
Stop. No feelings.
I'm good.

01:01.920 --> 01:03.620
And it'll stay good?

01:03.620 --> 01:05.330
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

01:05.330 --> 01:06.710
I just keep waiting
for the other shoe.

01:06.710 --> 01:07.880
What do you mean,
the other shoe?

01:07.880 --> 01:09.210
You know, like you saying
you wanted to have kids

01:09.210 --> 01:10.460
and then you don't
want to have kids.

01:10.460 --> 01:12.580
That was more like
a boot than a shoe.

01:12.580 --> 01:14.380
Actually, it was more like
an ass kicking.

01:14.380 --> 01:16.250
[ Both chuckle ]
♪ Give 'em what they want ♪

01:16.250 --> 01:18.420
Well,
I'll see you tonight.

01:18.420 --> 01:19.830
♪ Give 'em what they need ♪
Or not.

01:19.830 --> 01:22.500
No strings. No shoes.

01:22.500 --> 01:25.540
We can start work
on that book.

01:25.540 --> 01:28.290
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

01:31.620 --> 01:33.250
[ Birds chirping ]

01:33.250 --> 01:35.380
Arizona: Hey, Sofia?
Sofia!

01:35.380 --> 01:37.670
I've got three fluffy pancakes
patiently waiting for you.

01:37.670 --> 01:40.210
What --
Hey, why aren't you dressed?

01:40.210 --> 01:42.460
I put out your red shoes.
-I don't want my red shoes.

01:42.460 --> 01:44.120
Okay, well, at this point, I'll
settle for any shoes at all,

01:44.120 --> 01:45.380
so let's just put on --
let's put on shoes.

01:45.380 --> 01:47.460
[ Chuckles ]
What's wrong? Hey. What?

01:47.460 --> 01:48.920
What, are you sick?
Does your tummy hurt?

01:48.920 --> 01:50.250
-No.
-Okay, great.

01:50.250 --> 01:51.500
Then let's get up
and get dressed, okay?

01:51.500 --> 01:52.960
'Cause I have a huge day
at work, and you have school.

01:52.960 --> 01:54.460
So, what do you want first?
You want the shirt?

01:54.460 --> 01:56.420
You want pants?
You want -- Hey.

01:56.420 --> 01:58.500
Whoa.

01:58.500 --> 01:59.580
Hey.

02:01.620 --> 02:03.000
What's the matter?

02:03.000 --> 02:04.670
You can tell me.

02:04.670 --> 02:07.670
[ Crying ]
I want to go to New York.

02:07.670 --> 02:10.620
With my friends
and my other teacher

02:10.620 --> 02:13.120
who lets us draw
in our notebooks.

02:13.120 --> 02:15.000
And --
-And you miss your mommy, too.

02:17.040 --> 02:20.330
[ Sighs ] Sweetheart, hey,

02:20.330 --> 02:21.460
why don't you come to work
with me today?

02:23.250 --> 02:24.540
Okay?
All right, come on.

02:24.540 --> 02:25.580
All right.

02:25.580 --> 02:28.580
[ Siren wailing ]

02:28.580 --> 02:30.710
[ Indistinct conversations ]

02:30.710 --> 02:31.750
You paged.

02:31.750 --> 02:33.880
I paged.

02:33.880 --> 02:35.460
Do you need help
looking for something?

02:35.460 --> 02:37.920
You know what? I did.
But I think I see it now.

02:40.710 --> 02:41.960
Mmm.

02:41.960 --> 02:43.540
Does this door
have a lock?

02:43.540 --> 02:45.000
Mnh-mnh.
I don't think so.

02:45.000 --> 02:48.420
Maybe we should find a room
with a door with a lock.

02:48.420 --> 02:50.500
I don't have time for that.
I got a vagina to build.

02:51.170 --> 02:53.420
My vaginoplasty
for the contest.

02:53.420 --> 02:56.330
Right.
That surgery's today
with my mom and Richard.

02:56.330 --> 02:58.540
Wow.
Some families do puzzles.

03:01.210 --> 03:03.250
It's okay.
Tonight.

03:03.250 --> 03:04.960
Tonight I say
we cancel the reservation

03:04.960 --> 03:06.420
and have dinner
at my place.

03:06.420 --> 03:08.250
I got a lot of doors
and a lot of locks.

03:08.250 --> 03:09.960
-That sounds perfect.
-Oh, good.

03:12.710 --> 03:14.250
Yes.
[ Laughs ]

03:14.250 --> 03:16.620
Hey!

03:16.620 --> 03:17.620
Hey.
-Hey.

03:17.620 --> 03:19.080
Hello.

03:19.080 --> 03:20.460
[ Clears throat ]

03:20.460 --> 03:21.330
We should --
-Uh...

03:21.330 --> 03:23.670
Yep.

03:23.670 --> 03:25.250
Um, good luck
with your vagina.

03:25.250 --> 03:26.710
Don't...

03:28.120 --> 03:30.500
I'm just gonna --
Excuse me.

03:36.920 --> 03:39.710
[ Indistinct conversations ]

03:39.710 --> 03:41.040
What are you doing?

03:41.040 --> 03:42.330
All this stuff
has to get cleared out.

03:42.330 --> 03:44.000
That centrifuge that we stole
from oncology --

03:44.000 --> 03:45.040
that should go back.

03:45.040 --> 03:46.620
And do you and Alex
want a mouse?

03:46.620 --> 03:48.000
No.
No, no, no, no, no.

03:48.000 --> 03:49.330
The mouse stays.
I have news.

03:49.330 --> 03:50.830
I have great news.

03:50.830 --> 03:52.960
Oh. You got engaged, right?
Congratulations.

03:52.960 --> 03:56.500
No. No, no, no, it's --
I mean, yes. Thank you. But --

03:56.500 --> 03:59.120
No, no, no, no. [ Stammers ]
I was up all night.

03:59.120 --> 04:01.620
I found seven polymers
that could replace

04:01.620 --> 04:03.750
the one that hag Marie Cerone
stole from us.

04:03.750 --> 04:05.420
And I know she's your aunt or
whatever, but she's still a hag.

04:05.420 --> 04:07.250
Jo, let it go.

04:07.250 --> 04:09.790
We're outsmarted, outgunned,
outfunded.

04:09.790 --> 04:12.880
Even if we won the stupid
contest, she's way ahead of us.

04:12.880 --> 04:16.250
No. Okay, if you could just
look at any of these --

04:16.250 --> 04:17.710
Hey, you,
where are all the interns?

04:17.710 --> 04:19.170
Trauma Certification
with Hunt.

04:19.170 --> 04:20.210
Ugh.

04:20.210 --> 04:21.670
I have
a massive crush injury

04:21.670 --> 04:23.290
being helicoptered in
from Spokane

04:23.290 --> 04:25.000
and no one to teach about
massive crush injuries.

04:25.000 --> 04:26.790
-Take her, please.
-No!

04:26.790 --> 04:29.000
Yeah, you'll do.
With me.

04:29.000 --> 04:32.170
[ Telephone ringing ]

04:32.170 --> 04:33.880
Meh!

04:36.080 --> 04:37.790
[ Door closes ]

04:37.790 --> 04:39.580
[ Grunts ]
Woman on PA:
Dr. Boraff to the cap lab.

04:39.580 --> 04:41.170
Dr. Boraff to the cap lab.

04:41.170 --> 04:42.540
Ah, good for you.

04:42.540 --> 04:44.250
I always said you should
find more friends.

04:44.250 --> 04:46.210
[ Laughs ]
Uh, these are for --

04:46.210 --> 04:47.750
I know.
So, speaking of dummies,

04:47.750 --> 04:49.210
you know that thing
you said earlier

04:49.210 --> 04:51.040
about wanting and then
not wanting kids?

04:51.040 --> 04:52.580
You realize I had a brain tumor
at the time, right?

04:52.580 --> 04:54.330
Yeah, okay.
That's true,

04:54.330 --> 04:56.380
but you can't blame everything
on the tumor.

04:56.380 --> 04:58.080
No, I sort of can
because of

04:58.080 --> 05:00.580
the massive, heaping ball
that was pressed on my cerebrum.

05:00.580 --> 05:02.080
Okay, I thought you said
we were cool.

05:02.080 --> 05:04.670
Oh, I'm cool.
No. I am the coolest.

05:04.670 --> 05:06.460
But, you know,
even with the tumor,

05:06.460 --> 05:08.380
I still never
cheated on anyone.

05:08.380 --> 05:10.210
-Whoa. Wait.
-Good luck with your show.

05:10.210 --> 05:11.830
-[ Sighs ]
-Hey.

05:11.830 --> 05:14.040
Please let me run this thing
with you.

05:14.040 --> 05:15.750
Or --
Or I could run it for you.

05:15.750 --> 05:18.000
Without you. Just --
Just please let me run it.

05:18.000 --> 05:19.750
DeLuca's onboard to help.
We're good.

05:19.750 --> 05:21.420
I said please!

05:21.420 --> 05:23.380
Fine.
Breezeway in 10 minutes.

05:23.380 --> 05:25.120
Okay.

05:25.120 --> 05:27.250
Wow.

05:27.250 --> 05:30.960
And it turns out this woman had
an ax to grind with Ellis Grey.

05:30.960 --> 05:32.920
So, Dr. Grey's dropping out
of the contest?

05:32.920 --> 05:35.830
She's not giving us her patent,
so Dr. Grey is just quitting.

05:35.830 --> 05:37.420
It sucks.
-It does.

05:37.420 --> 05:39.880
But it does improve the odds
for my "AnalGlide."

05:39.880 --> 05:43.040
Hmm?
I'm trying out names
for my colonoscopy device.

05:43.040 --> 05:43.790
Anal-- No?

05:43.790 --> 05:45.460
Mnh. Mnh.

05:45.460 --> 05:46.830
Hello.

05:46.830 --> 05:48.120
I'm Chief Miranda Bailey.

05:48.120 --> 05:49.920
This is
Dr. Jo Wilson.

05:49.920 --> 05:51.790
Please, uh, present.

05:51.790 --> 05:53.920
Marjorie Kersey. 66.

05:53.920 --> 05:56.040
Sustained blunt trauma
to the abdomen and chest

05:56.040 --> 05:59.250
four days ago when
a 22-foot test apparatus...

05:59.250 --> 06:01.830
Electromagnet.
Big-ass electromagnet.

06:01.830 --> 06:03.330
...fell onto her.

06:03.330 --> 06:05.500
Hospitalized
at a community center,

06:05.500 --> 06:07.120
where her clinical course was
complicated

06:07.120 --> 06:09.290
by rhabdo
and acute kidney injury,

06:09.290 --> 06:11.170
all resolving, but...

06:11.170 --> 06:12.500
-Marge Kersey?
-Mm-hmm.

06:12.500 --> 06:14.330
...has recurrent
abdominal pain.

06:14.330 --> 06:16.250
Transferred here
for consultation.

06:16.250 --> 06:17.710
"Bargin' Marge" Kersey?

06:17.710 --> 06:18.710
The astronaut?

06:18.710 --> 06:21.620
Okay. Here we go.
Oh, my God.

06:21.620 --> 06:24.710
This woman has clocked
over 1,000 hours in space.

06:24.710 --> 06:27.790
In space!
Oh, my Lord,
we have a nerd!

06:27.790 --> 06:30.500
Oh, I'm a huge fan.

06:30.500 --> 06:33.750
But y-you won the Fundamental
Physics Prize twice.

06:33.750 --> 06:35.330
I know, hon.
I was there.

06:35.330 --> 06:36.670
[ Laughs ]

06:36.670 --> 06:38.460
Oh, is that like
the Nobel Prize?

06:38.460 --> 06:40.790
[ Chuckling ]
Ahh! The Nobel Prize wishes.

06:40.790 --> 06:44.210
Oh, Dr. Kersey, well,
it is an honor to meet you

06:44.210 --> 06:46.170
and a privilege
to treat you.

06:46.170 --> 06:47.500
Are you rhyming
on purpose?

06:47.500 --> 06:49.580
I -- What? No.

06:49.580 --> 06:52.750
I -- I've followed you
since I was a little girl.

06:52.750 --> 06:55.040
You are a trailblazer.

06:55.040 --> 06:57.290
Oh, my gosh,
thank you, hon.

06:57.290 --> 06:59.500
I hope you're prepared
to blaze a trail

06:59.500 --> 07:01.790
through my intestine
or whatnot.

07:01.790 --> 07:03.420
[ Laughing ]
Of course.

07:03.420 --> 07:08.210
Hey, um, what were you
working on, if I can ask?

07:08.210 --> 07:10.790
Can you say?
-I can say.

07:10.790 --> 07:13.540
Um, it's a temporal variance
spectrometer.

07:13.540 --> 07:18.420
It'll detect time-space changes
in the Higgs boson field

07:18.420 --> 07:22.040
and will eventually
control it.

07:23.920 --> 07:27.290
It sounds like -- Are you
building a time machine?

07:27.290 --> 07:29.120
Wow. You really are a nerd.
I'm impressed.

07:29.120 --> 07:31.380
A-A time machine?
Are you serious?

07:31.380 --> 07:34.620
You're building a time machine
for -- for NASA.

07:34.620 --> 07:37.540
Oh, no, I parted ways with NASA
years ago.

07:37.540 --> 07:40.290
I'm building it for me,
so I can travel to the future.

07:44.080 --> 07:45.460
[ Laughing ]
Yeah!

07:45.460 --> 07:46.620
-So cool.
-Uh-huh.

07:53.420 --> 07:54.540
So, your temporal
variance spectrometer,

07:54.540 --> 07:56.210
what,
creates a wormhole?

07:56.210 --> 07:58.460
No, no, that's a guy
in South Africa.

07:58.460 --> 08:01.040
He wants to send
little "beep-boop" signals

08:01.040 --> 08:02.920
through time dilation.

08:02.920 --> 08:04.920
I want to send people.

08:04.920 --> 08:06.040
Sending people
through time?

08:06.040 --> 08:07.960
That seems, uh --

08:07.960 --> 08:10.290
Bananas? Yeah. Apparently,
NASA thought so, too.

08:10.290 --> 08:11.920
Stop.

08:11.920 --> 08:15.420
Uh, hey, uh, why do you have me
set up for a head CT, anyway?

08:15.420 --> 08:16.670
You looking for
a tumor?

08:16.670 --> 08:18.040
Yeah, uh...

08:18.040 --> 08:20.170
Okay. No. Hold still.

08:20.170 --> 08:22.040
Just covering our bases.

08:22.040 --> 08:24.540
It's fine.
You're not the first ones

08:24.540 --> 08:26.460
who've looked at me
like I'm bat-crap crazy.

08:26.460 --> 08:28.080
You won't be the last.
-See? I told you.

08:28.080 --> 08:29.580
-Shh!
-I'm not the only one.

08:29.580 --> 08:31.120
[ Grunts ]

08:31.120 --> 08:32.580
You're fine.

08:32.580 --> 08:34.750
Big day, Mother.

08:34.750 --> 08:36.830
You ready?
Anything, uh, bothering you?

08:36.830 --> 08:38.120
I haven't said a word.

08:38.120 --> 08:39.420
You don't have to.
Your face did.

08:39.420 --> 08:41.330
My face
isn't saying anything.

08:41.330 --> 08:43.750
Richard, is my face
saying something?

08:43.750 --> 08:45.380
It's like reading Hemingway,
dear.

08:45.380 --> 08:47.420
[ Elevator dings ]

08:47.420 --> 08:48.500
Ahh.

08:48.500 --> 08:49.580
[ Sighs ]

08:49.580 --> 08:50.830
Good morning.

08:50.830 --> 08:52.750
-Mwah!
-Good morning, doctors.

08:52.750 --> 08:53.960
-Ah, good morning.
-Morning.

08:53.960 --> 08:55.290
You opening
a flower shop?

08:55.290 --> 08:57.420
Yeah.
They're from my boyfriend.

08:57.420 --> 08:59.380
He thinks he's hilarious.

08:59.380 --> 09:01.540
Sent me a book of
Georgia O'Keefe prints, too.

09:01.540 --> 09:02.580
[ Chuckles ]

09:02.580 --> 09:04.040
I never dreamed
this day would come.

09:04.040 --> 09:05.830
And I certainly
never dreamed

09:05.830 --> 09:08.120
that a mother and son
would build my vagina.

09:08.120 --> 09:09.500
And father.

09:09.500 --> 09:11.330
Stepfather, about a --
about a year and a half.

09:11.330 --> 09:12.330
So -- no offense.
-Mm.

09:12.330 --> 09:13.960
Uh, none taken.

09:13.960 --> 09:17.210
Well, family is family
is family.

09:17.210 --> 09:19.170
Like the saying goes.

09:19.170 --> 09:21.250
That's not a saying,
but okay.

09:21.250 --> 09:22.960
-Not to you, it's not.
-No one's ever said it.

09:22.960 --> 09:24.330
-[ Chuckles ]
-[ Clears throat ]

09:24.330 --> 09:26.080
Is everything okay?

09:26.080 --> 09:28.790
-Yes.
-Mm-hmm. Oh, yeah.

09:28.790 --> 09:31.500
Because part of me feels like a
little kid on Christmas morning.

09:31.500 --> 09:34.080
But the other part is
a world-class physician

09:34.080 --> 09:35.290
who knows
you're dealing with

09:35.290 --> 09:37.500
the most sensitive organ
in the body.

09:37.500 --> 09:39.000
I can't afford
any distractions.

09:39.000 --> 09:40.330
Michelle, I hear you.

09:40.330 --> 09:41.790
Let me assure you
that my mind is not

09:41.790 --> 09:43.830
anywhere but right here,
in this surgery.

09:43.830 --> 09:45.500
Shall we do this?

09:45.500 --> 09:46.960
[ Breathes deeply ]

09:46.960 --> 09:47.960
Yes.

09:47.960 --> 09:49.500
[ Laughing ]
Let's do this.

09:49.500 --> 09:52.120
Yeah. Oh, all right,
bring it in. Nice.

09:52.120 --> 09:55.040
[ Both laughing ]

09:55.040 --> 09:56.380
-Ohh.
-Hey.

09:56.380 --> 09:58.330
Oh, wow, this is
where the party is.

09:58.330 --> 10:00.460
Dr. Robbins.
Who is the new intern?

10:00.460 --> 10:02.250
This is my daughter,
Sofia.

10:02.250 --> 10:03.710
And this must be
the infamous Noah.

10:03.710 --> 10:05.330
It sure is.
Noah, honey, say hi.

10:05.330 --> 10:07.170
-Hi.
-Hi.

10:07.170 --> 10:08.580
Liz, when did the pain start
and where?

10:08.580 --> 10:09.580
I was on my way
to his school.

10:09.580 --> 10:11.040
It's here
in my lower back.

10:11.040 --> 10:12.290
Is it stabbing
or shooting?

10:12.290 --> 10:14.250
-No. More like pressure.
-All right.

10:14.250 --> 10:15.670
Um, hey, Noah,
can you come over here

10:15.670 --> 10:17.250
and sit on the chairs
while I give your mom an exam?

10:17.250 --> 10:19.500
-Want to see my robot monster?
-'Kay.

10:19.500 --> 10:23.250
[ Both laughing ]

10:23.250 --> 10:25.420
He's a full-blown prodigy,
and I'm definitely not biased.

10:25.420 --> 10:26.710
Well, it has been a while

10:26.710 --> 10:28.460
since I've heard Sofia
laugh like that.

10:28.460 --> 10:29.580
Noah seems to laugh
a lot.

10:29.580 --> 10:31.540
Yeah, he's always been
a happy kid.

10:31.540 --> 10:33.920
Good.

10:33.920 --> 10:35.500
All righty.

10:35.500 --> 10:37.750
Let's see...

10:37.750 --> 10:39.830
-Okay.
-...what we got going on.

10:39.830 --> 10:41.040
You're gonna feel a little bit
of pressure.

10:41.040 --> 10:42.540
Okay.

10:42.540 --> 10:45.120
[ Heartbeat ]

10:45.120 --> 10:47.170
You said
I could carry to term.

10:47.170 --> 10:49.000
Liz, you have
Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome,

10:49.000 --> 10:50.830
so I said that we would try
to get you to term.

10:50.830 --> 10:52.170
But I'm a --
I'm a little worried

10:52.170 --> 10:53.580
that you have
an incompetent cervix.

10:53.580 --> 10:55.540
Well, that sounds...
rude.

10:55.540 --> 10:58.500
Well [chuckles] your uterus
is putting pressure

10:58.500 --> 11:00.250
on your cervix,
causing it to open.

11:00.250 --> 11:02.750
And then your amniotic sac
is bulging through.

11:02.750 --> 11:04.540
And the monitor shows that you
might be having contractions,

11:04.540 --> 11:06.290
so let's admit you and let's try
and stop them.

11:06.290 --> 11:08.710
Contractions?
But she's only 23 weeks.

11:08.710 --> 11:10.380
Right. That's why I'm gonna do
everything I can

11:10.380 --> 11:12.000
to make sure that she stays
exactly where she is.

11:12.000 --> 11:13.380
[ Chuckles ]

11:13.380 --> 11:15.330
Hey, should I start
freaking out now?

11:15.330 --> 11:18.420
No, because that would be
neither helpful nor necessary.

11:18.420 --> 11:19.750
Hey, Noah,
can you come, um,

11:19.750 --> 11:21.620
hang out with your mom
for a second?

11:21.620 --> 11:22.670
[ Laughing ]

11:22.670 --> 11:25.460
Hey, honey.

11:25.460 --> 11:27.420
Um, okay, uh,
I will see you soon.

11:27.420 --> 11:28.500
-Okay.
-All right.

11:28.500 --> 11:30.170
Yeah. See you.

11:34.460 --> 11:36.000
Oh, hey. Hey.

11:36.000 --> 11:36.960
There you are.
What are you doing?

11:36.960 --> 11:38.380
Packing it in.
You okay?

11:38.380 --> 11:40.040
No. Something happened.

11:40.040 --> 11:41.420
What's wrong?

11:41.420 --> 11:42.540
[ Groans ]

11:42.540 --> 11:44.750
Are you quitting the contest,
too?

11:44.750 --> 11:46.960
Uh, no.
I was making out with Jackson,

11:46.960 --> 11:50.250
and we got caught by his mother
and my -- and Richard.

11:50.250 --> 11:52.380
I mean, we're all fine.
We're all adults.

11:52.380 --> 11:53.960
And Richard
isn't even really my dad,

11:53.960 --> 11:56.040
but I suddenly feel like
he is my father.

11:56.040 --> 11:58.000
And I -- I feel like I felt
when I was 15,

11:58.000 --> 12:00.790
and when I was 15,
I was 12.

12:00.790 --> 12:03.380
[ Sighs ]
-Jackson?

12:03.380 --> 12:05.460
Oh, crap, I didn't tell you
about that.

12:05.460 --> 12:07.290
Wait a second. You're dropping
out of the contest?

12:07.290 --> 12:09.880
Marie Cerone wanted me to
rename the Grey Method

12:09.880 --> 12:11.500
the Grey-Cerone Method
and...

12:11.500 --> 12:13.500
That's crazy.

12:13.500 --> 12:15.420
Yeah. I couldn't do it.
That would kill Ellis.

12:15.420 --> 12:17.540
And I've already watched her die
once, so...

12:17.540 --> 12:20.080
Uh, well, you can't let her
take this away from you.

12:20.080 --> 12:21.380
I won't let you.

12:21.380 --> 12:23.420
No, Maggie. Stop. It's fine.
Listen, you've never

12:23.420 --> 12:25.040
had your hopes and dreams
crushed by our mother,

12:25.040 --> 12:27.460
but for me it was an annual
occurrence, so, really.

12:27.460 --> 12:29.670
I'm pissed,
but I'll get over it.
[ Pager beeps ]

12:29.670 --> 12:31.500
Ugh. I got to go.
Consult.

12:31.500 --> 12:35.420
But Jackson -- You're --
You're -- Jackson?

12:35.420 --> 12:38.420
Oh, yes, I'm seeing Jackson,
and it's wonderful.

12:38.420 --> 12:40.080
We haven't had sex yet,
but I hope we will tonight,

12:40.080 --> 12:41.500
so --
Oh, I won't need a ride home.

12:41.500 --> 12:42.920
Okay, bye.

12:42.920 --> 12:45.170
Wow. Okay.

12:45.170 --> 12:47.580
Welcome to
Trauma Certification.

12:47.580 --> 12:52.920
Moments ago, a Cessna has
crashed into a Greyhound bus.

12:52.920 --> 12:54.710
The EVAC helicopter
is on its way.

12:54.710 --> 12:56.170
Yeah, yeah,
maybe somewhere else.

12:56.170 --> 12:58.580
No, not here.
What happened here is that

12:58.580 --> 13:01.380
the EVAC helicopter also crashed
and is up in flames right now.

13:01.380 --> 13:02.620
All right,
people are dying.

13:02.620 --> 13:04.710
It is your job
to their lives.

13:04.710 --> 13:06.170
What are the rules?

13:06.170 --> 13:08.250
This is real life,
Bloodbank.

13:08.250 --> 13:11.120
In a harsh
and uncaring world,

13:11.120 --> 13:14.290
the only rule is
there are no rules.

13:14.290 --> 13:16.790
People are bleeding!
People are dying!

13:16.790 --> 13:18.540
Go! Go! Go!

13:18.540 --> 13:20.290
Why aren't you moving?

13:20.290 --> 13:21.880
Let's go. Hustle.

13:21.880 --> 13:23.210
Grab a body.

13:23.210 --> 13:24.620
Work on your patient.

13:24.620 --> 13:26.620
Get to work.

13:26.620 --> 13:27.750
I want to see hustle.

13:36.750 --> 13:37.710
There's air
in the biliary system.

13:37.710 --> 13:39.330
Wilson, thoughts?

13:39.330 --> 13:42.620
Probably a fistula from
the liver to the duodenum.

13:42.620 --> 13:44.000
We'll have to ligate.

13:44.000 --> 13:45.830
Good. Uh,
do we need to open the chest?

13:45.830 --> 13:50.250
No. I can treat the abscess
by infusing TPA and DNase

13:50.250 --> 13:51.330
through the chest tube
while you're in there.

13:51.330 --> 13:53.290
Well,
her brain scan is clear.

13:53.290 --> 13:55.170
And it's a sexy brain.
She's 66?

13:55.170 --> 13:56.460
Oh, well,
if you believe her,

13:56.460 --> 13:59.210
then she's 166
'cause she's a time-traveler.

13:59.210 --> 14:01.210
Time travel?
Like wormholes?

14:01.210 --> 14:02.460
Exactly!

14:03.750 --> 14:05.880
-What are we looking at here?
-Oh, wait. "Wormhole" --

14:05.880 --> 14:08.000
that's a great name
for your device!
[ Stammers ]

14:08.000 --> 14:11.000
Bailey is looking for names
for her...colon thingy.

14:11.000 --> 14:12.330
No, I'm not.

14:12.330 --> 14:13.290
"Ass Gasket" --
that's a good one.

14:13.290 --> 14:15.500
God,
if I could go back in time.

14:15.500 --> 14:18.080
No, you can't.
Time doesn't go backwards.

14:18.080 --> 14:19.250
Read your Einstein,
Einstein.

14:19.250 --> 14:22.120
The men I would not
have slept with.

14:22.120 --> 14:23.250
And the one woman
I would have.

14:23.250 --> 14:24.540
"Crack Jack"?

14:24.540 --> 14:26.920
Maggie: I would go back
and undo this morning.

14:26.920 --> 14:29.330
Well, I would -- I would
kill Hitler and end slavery,

14:29.330 --> 14:31.040
and then I would go
straight to this morning.

14:31.040 --> 14:32.500
Oh, no, wait.
I would go back

14:32.500 --> 14:34.830
and see what happened between
Ellis Grey and Marie Cerone.

14:34.830 --> 14:36.170
"Fanny Spanner."

14:36.170 --> 14:38.120
-Karev, stop.
[ Light laughter ]

14:38.120 --> 14:40.210
Hey, your patient's hypotensive,
hypoxic, and tachycardic.

14:40.210 --> 14:41.330
What did you do?

14:41.330 --> 14:43.080
So, we did bilateral
chest tubes first.

14:43.080 --> 14:44.790
There was no improvement,
so we checked for a JVD,

14:44.790 --> 14:46.290
muffled heart sounds,
and pulsus paradoxus.

14:46.290 --> 14:47.750
Good.
Your patient's gonna survive

14:47.750 --> 14:50.000
and fight for
another five minutes.
[ Siren wailing ]

14:50.000 --> 14:52.000
Schmitt, your patient just
aspirated in his own blood.

14:52.000 --> 14:54.170
Dead.

14:54.170 --> 14:55.920
Hellmouth,
your patient's pregnant.

14:55.920 --> 14:57.290
He's a dude with a beard.

14:57.290 --> 15:00.380
She's a bearded lady
and she's a mom

15:00.380 --> 15:01.670
and her baby's just gone into
fetal distress.

15:01.670 --> 15:03.040
What do you do?

15:03.040 --> 15:05.040
Uh, I-I cut the --
No, I use that --

15:05.040 --> 15:06.330
Too late. Both dead.

15:06.330 --> 15:07.460
-Kepner, Kepner.
-What?

15:07.460 --> 15:08.670
They're not gonna
learn anything

15:08.670 --> 15:09.880
if you keep
killing their patients.

15:09.880 --> 15:11.250
[ Chuckles ]

15:11.250 --> 15:13.000
Pow! Piece of shrapnel
from the plane wing

15:13.000 --> 15:14.710
just fell out of the sky
and into your boyfriend's body.

15:14.710 --> 15:16.080
What now, Bello?

15:16.080 --> 15:17.170
DeLuca:
T-The plane wing hit me?

15:17.170 --> 15:19.120
Oh, yeah!
Another plane is crashing.

15:19.120 --> 15:20.790
Who saw that coming?
-C-Can she do that to a doctor?

15:20.790 --> 15:22.250
It feels like cheating.

15:22.250 --> 15:24.080
You're hurt and bleeding,
DeLuca. Get down.

15:24.080 --> 15:25.620
Ahh.

15:25.620 --> 15:27.380
I said hurt and bleeding,
not hot and bothered.

15:27.380 --> 15:28.500
Aaaaaah!

15:28.500 --> 15:29.620
All right,
what are you gonna do, Bello?

15:29.620 --> 15:30.710
Is she cheating?

15:30.710 --> 15:32.040
Uh, Kepner,
you got this?

15:32.040 --> 15:33.330
I need to step out
for a few secs.
Yep.

15:33.330 --> 15:34.580
Whoa, whoa, wait.
Y-You're leaving us?

15:34.580 --> 15:35.710
-Oh, yeah. Yeah, I am.
-Hey, you can't talk.

15:35.710 --> 15:37.420
You're bleeding
from your femoral artery.

15:37.420 --> 15:39.170
What's it gonna be --
him or the patient, huh?

15:39.170 --> 15:40.540
Don't let lust
cloud your judgment.

15:40.540 --> 15:42.380
What's it gonna be?
Hey, more pain!

15:42.380 --> 15:43.790
-Aaaaah!
-More!

15:43.790 --> 15:45.250
Aaaaaaaaaaah!
Aaaaaaaaaaah!

15:45.250 --> 15:46.620
There you go.

15:46.620 --> 15:48.290
-Aaaaaaaaaaah!
-There you go.

15:48.290 --> 15:50.080
First I have to ask Dr. Shepherd
and Dr. Karev

15:50.080 --> 15:51.420
some important questions,
okay?

15:51.420 --> 15:53.500
-How's it going, rugrat?
-Hey, Dr. Alex.

15:53.500 --> 15:55.620
I have a patient whose son
laughs all the time.

15:55.620 --> 15:57.960
Is that bad? Because then
I've been doing this all wrong.

15:57.960 --> 16:00.250
No,
I-I had a case back in peds.

16:00.250 --> 16:03.330
It's --
It's uncontrollable laughing.

16:03.330 --> 16:05.290
It sounds sort of hollow,
peculiar.

16:05.290 --> 16:07.170
-You're thinking H.H.?
-Gelastic seizures?

16:07.170 --> 16:09.500
-What's a seizure?
-Oh, it's when --

16:09.500 --> 16:10.750
It's when something's hurt
inside your brain.

16:10.750 --> 16:12.460
Is Noah sick?

16:12.460 --> 16:13.790
I thought
his mommy was sick.

16:13.790 --> 16:15.750
Hey, you got a sec?

16:15.750 --> 16:17.420
Yeah.

16:17.420 --> 16:20.330
Um, so, can you see him today?
Now?

16:20.330 --> 16:22.750
Okay.

16:22.750 --> 16:23.830
I'm not a cheater.

16:23.830 --> 16:24.920
I never said you were.

16:24.920 --> 16:26.210
You implied it.

16:26.210 --> 16:27.540
I mean, I have cheated,

16:27.540 --> 16:29.040
but that doesn't
make me a "cheater."

16:29.040 --> 16:31.920
Ah, tomato, "tomahto,"
potato, adulterer.

16:31.920 --> 16:33.750
Listen, you were the one
who told me to go to Teddy.

16:33.750 --> 16:35.040
And you listened.

16:35.040 --> 16:36.290
What was I
supposed to say?

16:36.290 --> 16:39.790
"Hey, Amelia.
That sounds crazy.

16:39.790 --> 16:42.420
Hey, Amelia.
Teddy and I aren't like that.

16:42.420 --> 16:44.960
Hey, Amelia.
I'm gonna be a good husband

16:44.960 --> 16:48.210
and not cheat on you with
this woman I have history with."

16:48.210 --> 16:50.620
You had options
because you, unlike me,

16:50.620 --> 16:52.000
did not have
a brain tumor.

16:52.000 --> 16:53.460
Okay,
that is not fair.

16:53.460 --> 16:55.250
Isn't it?

16:55.250 --> 16:56.880
Okay.

16:56.880 --> 16:58.790
Teddy is my...

16:59.920 --> 17:01.120
She's Teddy.

17:01.120 --> 17:02.540
She knows me.

17:02.540 --> 17:04.960
And she's always been there
for me if I've needed her.

17:04.960 --> 17:07.210
And tumor or not,
you weren't.

17:07.210 --> 17:09.960
So I didn't feel like
I was cheating on you.

17:09.960 --> 17:12.420
When you told me to go to her,
it felt right.

17:12.420 --> 17:14.120
And I'm sorry if that hurts,
but it is the truth.

17:17.290 --> 17:19.120
Wow.

17:19.120 --> 17:20.960
Our marriage
didn't stand a chance.

17:20.960 --> 17:22.120
What?

17:22.120 --> 17:23.750
Teddy.

17:23.750 --> 17:25.210
She's your tumor.

17:28.330 --> 17:30.000
What?

17:34.290 --> 17:37.040
The Party is now
the world's worst hangover.

17:37.040 --> 17:40.290
I, um -- I pre-oxygenated the
patient, rapid-sequenced him.

17:40.290 --> 17:42.210
And then
I inserted an ET tube,

17:42.210 --> 17:44.330
and then I checked the position
with a CO2 indicator.

17:44.330 --> 17:46.330
All right,
Hellmouth's team is winning.

17:46.330 --> 17:48.250
The rest of you
are losers.
Hey!

17:48.250 --> 17:50.380
Kepner, is the hose
really necessary?

17:50.380 --> 17:53.120
Oh, you know what? Whining
doesn't save dying people.

17:53.120 --> 17:56.580
Speaking of dying people, your
boyfriend's bleeding out, Bello.

17:56.580 --> 17:58.000
Okay,
I apply a tourniquet onto his --

17:58.000 --> 17:59.420
No, no, no.
ABCs, remember?

17:59.420 --> 18:00.790
No. You're bleeding out.
You can't help me.

18:00.790 --> 18:01.750
Well, I don't want to die.

18:01.750 --> 18:04.120
[ Speaking Italian ]

18:04.120 --> 18:05.080
You don't think
I understand you?

18:05.080 --> 18:06.580
Spanish is pretty close
to Italian.

18:06.580 --> 18:07.750
[ Speaking Spanish ]

18:13.170 --> 18:14.620
Kepner,
what are you doing?

18:14.620 --> 18:16.170
April: What? Oh.

18:16.170 --> 18:18.170
I got rained on when
I did my Trauma Cert.

18:18.170 --> 18:20.040
Yeah,
because it was raining.

18:20.040 --> 18:21.580
[ Speaking French ]

18:23.250 --> 18:25.620
I don't like this game.
I don't like this game!

18:25.620 --> 18:26.670
You're breaking them,
Kepner.

18:26.670 --> 18:27.790
Look,
they're losing their minds.

18:27.790 --> 18:29.500
Hey, keep up those compressions,
Bloodbank!

18:29.500 --> 18:31.080
You're losing her!

18:31.080 --> 18:33.000
[ Cellphone vibrating
and ringing ]

18:33.000 --> 18:34.710
Damn it.
I got to go the ICU.

18:34.710 --> 18:36.420
This was getting so fun.

18:36.420 --> 18:38.210
Hey, make sure he doesn't
stop compressions.

18:38.210 --> 18:40.620
There's no crying
in Trauma Cert!

18:40.620 --> 18:42.250
Here you go.

18:46.170 --> 18:48.330
-[ Gasps, sighs ]
-It's okay. It's okay.

18:48.330 --> 18:49.960
Just -- Just breathe.
Just breathe.

18:49.960 --> 18:51.120
She's gone. She's gone.

18:51.120 --> 18:52.580
[ Crying ]
[ Siren wailing ]

18:52.580 --> 18:56.620
It's okay.
Just -- Just breathe it out.

18:56.620 --> 18:58.460
Then Dr. Webber will use a
laparoscope

18:58.460 --> 19:00.750
to extract a piece
of the peritoneum.

19:00.750 --> 19:02.960
Richard: Minimally invasive,
minimal scarring.

19:02.960 --> 19:04.380
Thanks for
letting me know.

19:04.380 --> 19:07.500
Thanks for not
hiding it from me...
Mom, come on.

19:07.500 --> 19:09.420
...like you've been hiding
Maggie Pierce.
Yeah, I get it.

19:09.420 --> 19:11.750
Uh, let's talk
about this later.

19:11.750 --> 19:14.290
Over pie.
You know what?
Yes, I am seeing Maggie Pierce.

19:14.290 --> 19:16.380
And, no, it's none
of your business.
None of my business?

19:16.380 --> 19:18.210
My love life isn't
any of your concern, no.

19:18.210 --> 19:20.540
It never was and never will be.
-What about your wife -- April?

19:20.540 --> 19:21.960
Guys --
You all work together
all the time.
Ex-wife.

19:21.960 --> 19:24.120
Of all the places on earth
for you to dip your wick,

19:24.120 --> 19:25.210
you chose --
-Out of line, all right?

19:25.210 --> 19:26.670
Come on.
Oh, child, please.
Guys!

19:26.670 --> 19:28.120
What?
What?

19:28.120 --> 19:29.250
[ Stammers ]

19:29.250 --> 19:31.580
Oh, now look
what you did.

19:31.580 --> 19:35.750
-What I did?
-Yeah. You just did.

19:35.750 --> 19:37.620
Michelle, stop.

19:37.620 --> 19:39.040
Michelle, it's not what
it looks like, all right?

19:39.040 --> 19:40.960
It isn't?

19:40.960 --> 19:42.250
'Cause it looks like
my doctors

19:42.250 --> 19:43.750
don't have their heads
in the game.

19:43.750 --> 19:45.290
My mother's upset about
a personal matter.

19:45.290 --> 19:46.960
It's nothing, really.
-It's not nothing.

19:46.960 --> 19:48.420
-Mom, come on.
-No.

19:48.420 --> 19:50.500
Whatever happens in there,
I'm gonna leave here,

19:50.500 --> 19:51.540
for better or worse,

19:51.540 --> 19:54.380
with my life and body
permanently altered.

19:54.380 --> 19:56.500
And I would rather it not
be for the worse.

19:56.500 --> 19:59.420
So, whatever
this "nothing" is...

19:59.420 --> 20:00.500
figure it out

20:00.500 --> 20:01.920
because you're not
cutting into me

20:01.920 --> 20:04.080
until I have
your full attention.

20:04.080 --> 20:09.040
♪♪

20:16.120 --> 20:17.420
So, as your liver was healing,
a fistula developed,

20:17.420 --> 20:19.710
uh, sort of
an accidental bridge

20:19.710 --> 20:21.830
between the liver
and the small bowel.

20:21.830 --> 20:24.170
-Sounds like a design flaw.
-It is.

20:24.170 --> 20:25.670
We'll have to go in
and dissect it out.

20:25.670 --> 20:28.250
Mm.
Almost poetic, right?

20:28.250 --> 20:31.290
I'm searching for ways
to make time bridges in space,

20:31.290 --> 20:33.170
and one forms inside me.

20:33.170 --> 20:34.790
Too bad I hate poetry.

20:34.790 --> 20:36.790
See, I-I respect
what you're doing,

20:36.790 --> 20:40.250
but I worry about you
being out there all alone,

20:40.250 --> 20:42.170
working with all that
heavy equipment --

20:42.170 --> 20:43.500
-On a lunatic's errand.
-No --

20:43.500 --> 20:45.500
Yeah. I get it.

20:45.500 --> 20:47.380
I may never crack it.

20:47.380 --> 20:50.420
But I never want to be
a person who says, "No."

20:50.420 --> 20:53.580
Like, you say, "No,"
and you stop the future cold.

20:53.580 --> 20:55.830
All you have is your past,
your mistakes, your regrets.

20:55.830 --> 21:00.670
But you say, "Maybe,"
and the whole world opens up.

21:00.670 --> 21:02.620
The past is gone,

21:02.620 --> 21:05.790
and there are a million futures
you can have.

21:07.580 --> 21:09.830
[ Gasping ]
Okay, Liz, I need you to
take deep breaths, okay?

21:09.830 --> 21:11.670
Deep breaths slowly,
slowly.

21:11.670 --> 21:13.750
[ Breathes deeply ]

21:13.750 --> 21:14.790
She's scared, Mommy.

21:14.790 --> 21:16.210
I know, honey. I know.

21:16.210 --> 21:17.750
I know you're scared.
I know you're --

21:17.750 --> 21:19.670
It's just his laugh.

21:19.670 --> 21:21.170
It's just a laugh.
This is so stupid.

21:21.170 --> 21:22.420
I shouldn't have let them
take him.

21:22.420 --> 21:23.790
It's just an MRI.

21:23.790 --> 21:25.380
There's no radiation.
He's not gonna get hurt,

21:25.380 --> 21:26.670
and it's better to be
safe than sorry, right?

21:26.670 --> 21:28.330
You couldn't wait?

21:28.330 --> 21:29.920
You couldn't wait
till I'm not --

21:29.920 --> 21:31.750
t-till my baby's not --

21:31.750 --> 21:34.170
[voice breaking] to tell me that
my son's laughter might be --

21:34.170 --> 21:35.500
Liz, I really couldn't wait,
okay?

21:35.500 --> 21:38.380
I'm -- I am so sorry,
but Noah's laughs --

21:38.380 --> 21:41.290
if they are seizures,
every time that they happen,

21:41.290 --> 21:42.710
they are doing damage
to his brain,

21:42.710 --> 21:44.880
and I need those doctors to do
everything that they can

21:44.880 --> 21:46.750
to make them stop them
immediately.

21:48.290 --> 21:52.250
Sweetie,
I'm sorry I'm such a crybaby.

21:52.250 --> 21:54.710
This must be pretty scary
for you, huh?

21:54.710 --> 21:57.290
All this grown-up stuff.

21:57.290 --> 21:59.120
I just hope
that Noah's okay.

22:00.830 --> 22:02.330
[ Screaming ]

22:02.330 --> 22:03.500
Okay, hold on.
Hold on. Hold on.

22:03.500 --> 22:04.670
I know -- I know that
it's really hard.

22:04.670 --> 22:06.420
I know that it's really hard,
but if you move,

22:06.420 --> 22:07.380
you could rupture
the amniotic sac.

22:07.380 --> 22:09.330
And if it ruptures,
then I can't help your baby.

22:09.330 --> 22:10.750
Okay.
Mommy.
Stay still. I know, honey.

22:10.750 --> 22:12.080
You know what, Ella,
can you please take her?

22:12.080 --> 22:13.540
Ella,
I need you to take Sofia.

22:13.540 --> 22:14.960
Hey, book an O.R.
and get me some orderlies, okay?

22:14.960 --> 22:16.420
Mommy,
I want to stay with you.

22:16.420 --> 22:17.960
Sofia, I need you to
get out of here now!

22:17.960 --> 22:19.580
All right, Liz...
-Yeah?

22:19.580 --> 22:21.250
...I'm gonna lower your
head, and we're gonna
take you to the O.R.

22:21.250 --> 22:22.920
W-Wait. O.R.?
I need to see Noah first.

22:22.920 --> 22:24.540
We don't have time.

22:24.540 --> 22:25.880
[ Crying ]

22:25.880 --> 22:27.790
It's gonna be okay, okay?

22:27.790 --> 22:29.000
We got to move. We got to move.
Let's go!

22:32.040 --> 22:35.830
[ Laughing ]

22:35.830 --> 22:37.540
[ Laughs ]
Stop it.

22:37.540 --> 22:39.330
If we can't get him to stay
still, we can't get a good scan.

22:39.330 --> 22:40.960
Hey, Noah, what's orange
and sounds like a parrot?

22:41.960 --> 22:42.960
A carrot!

22:42.960 --> 22:44.710
[ Laughs ]

22:44.710 --> 22:46.460
You are zero help.

22:46.460 --> 22:48.750
Noah, how do you
get a tissue to dance?

22:48.750 --> 22:50.250
You put a little boogie
in it.

22:50.250 --> 22:52.540
[ Laughs ]

22:52.540 --> 22:54.330
[ Chuckles ] I'm just trying to
hear his real laugh.

22:56.120 --> 22:57.330
[ Chuckles ]

22:59.210 --> 23:02.250
Okay, Noah,
you and Dr. Karev

23:02.250 --> 23:04.750
are gonna play a game
called Statue.

23:04.750 --> 23:07.710
Whichever one of you moves first
loses.

23:07.710 --> 23:09.290
Okay, Statue game.

23:09.290 --> 23:13.710
Ready?
One, two, three.

23:13.710 --> 23:15.380
[ Computer beeping ]

23:15.380 --> 23:16.620
[ Keys clacking ]

23:16.620 --> 23:19.120
They're seizures, right?

23:19.120 --> 23:20.670
Yeah.

23:20.670 --> 23:23.580
Yeah, they are.

23:23.580 --> 23:26.120
[ Laughing ]

23:27.460 --> 23:29.830
Did I win?

23:29.830 --> 23:31.830
I don't know what was wrong
with that lawyer woman.

23:31.830 --> 23:34.750
She was accomplished,
and she was attractive.

23:34.750 --> 23:35.960
So is Maggie, Mom.

23:35.960 --> 23:37.290
This is not a contest.

23:37.290 --> 23:39.210
Oh, really?
What is it?

23:41.710 --> 23:43.420
Don't look at me.
I can't answer that for you.

23:43.420 --> 23:44.830
Why not?

23:44.830 --> 23:47.460
I don't understand why you're
not more upset over this mess.

23:47.460 --> 23:49.000
Oh, I'm plenty upset.

23:49.000 --> 23:50.540
-Thank you.
-You are?

23:50.540 --> 23:52.420
Not with them,
Catherine.

23:52.420 --> 23:53.500
With you.

23:53.500 --> 23:55.420
Excuse me?

23:55.420 --> 23:57.290
Nothing's ever good enough
for your child.

23:57.290 --> 23:58.830
I get it,
that you have strong feelings

23:58.830 --> 24:00.210
about who Jackson dates.

24:00.210 --> 24:01.460
Any parent would.

24:01.460 --> 24:03.500
This is not
about Maggie.

24:03.500 --> 24:06.960
No, it's not about Maggie --
because she's brilliant.

24:06.960 --> 24:09.330
She's skilled,
and she's kind.

24:09.330 --> 24:11.620
And any mother in her right mind
would be elated

24:11.620 --> 24:13.330
that she'd deign
to date their son.

24:13.330 --> 24:15.620
-Damn!
-Don't "damn" me.

24:15.620 --> 24:18.080
You have my blessing, son,

24:18.080 --> 24:20.540
but if I hear that
you've hurt Maggie in any way,

24:20.540 --> 24:21.460
I'm gonna come after you.

24:21.460 --> 24:23.000
Damn.

24:23.000 --> 24:25.750
Now,
you two let me know if

24:25.750 --> 24:27.460
we're doing this groundbreaking
surgery today or not.

24:27.460 --> 24:29.120
In the meantime,
I got patients.

24:31.750 --> 24:33.040
[ Door opens ]

24:33.040 --> 24:34.500
[ Indistinct conversations ]

24:34.500 --> 24:36.170
[ Door closes ]
[ Sighs heavily ]

24:36.170 --> 24:37.920
[ Telephone rings ]

24:37.920 --> 24:39.830
[ Indistinct conversations ]

24:39.830 --> 24:41.460
Michelle.

24:41.460 --> 24:44.380
Michelle,
we want to apologize.

24:44.380 --> 24:45.670
Michelle,
we were out of line earlier.

24:45.670 --> 24:47.040
Catherine: We've settled
our differences.

24:47.040 --> 24:49.000
We're ready to get back to work
if you'll have us.

24:49.000 --> 24:51.290
That's a load of crap.

24:51.290 --> 24:52.380
What's it about?

24:52.380 --> 24:54.670
-No.
-[ Sighs ]

24:54.670 --> 24:57.210
It's about
a woman he's seeing.

24:57.210 --> 24:58.460
No, that's not
Michelle's concern.

24:58.460 --> 24:59.580
It's not even yours.

24:59.580 --> 25:00.790
Is he dating garbage?

25:00.790 --> 25:02.580
No. She's brilliant.

25:02.580 --> 25:04.380
She's lovely.
She's --

25:04.380 --> 25:06.120
And Mom thinks
she's my stepsister.

25:06.120 --> 25:08.500
Oh.
But it's not like
we grew up together, okay?

25:08.500 --> 25:10.250
We're -- Didn't even meet
until we were adults.

25:10.250 --> 25:11.880
It's --
It's not that.
That's not even the main thing.

25:11.880 --> 25:13.380
It's not about her.

25:13.380 --> 25:14.750
Great.
So it's about me.

25:14.750 --> 25:16.540
It's about Richard.

25:18.290 --> 25:20.210
When your father left,

25:20.210 --> 25:22.920
I just closed off
a part of my heart,

25:22.920 --> 25:25.380
slammed the door,
nailed shut...

25:25.380 --> 25:27.580
until Richard Webber
came along

25:27.580 --> 25:31.880
and shook me like
I didn't know I could shake.

25:31.880 --> 25:35.620
And when I saw you and Maggie
today, I...

25:35.620 --> 25:37.540
[ Sighs ]

25:37.540 --> 25:38.920
All I could think was,

25:38.920 --> 25:42.080
"Richard is gonna take her side,
like I would take yours,"

25:42.080 --> 25:44.040
like he just did.

25:44.040 --> 25:47.290
Then what if
we can't reconcile that?

25:50.210 --> 25:53.880
Jackson,
I want you to have love.

25:53.880 --> 25:56.670
I just don't want it
to cost me mine.

25:58.790 --> 26:00.210
Richard's not my father,
Mom.

26:00.210 --> 26:03.500
I know.
He's my husband.

26:03.500 --> 26:04.960
No. I'm saying

26:04.960 --> 26:06.750
you should give him
a little more credit than that.

26:06.750 --> 26:08.830
I've met my father.

26:08.830 --> 26:11.210
Richard ain't him.

26:11.210 --> 26:12.330
He's a lot better
than that.

26:15.210 --> 26:17.880
Okay. Good.

26:17.880 --> 26:20.080
Now hug it out.
Come on.

26:21.960 --> 26:24.380
[ Both sigh ]

26:26.040 --> 26:27.920
It's a shortcut between
two points in space.

26:27.920 --> 26:30.420
You enter the wormhole,
space folds like a taco,

26:30.420 --> 26:31.710
and then you come out
the other side.

26:31.710 --> 26:32.880
And the other side
is the past?

26:32.880 --> 26:35.500
No, you can't travel
to the past, but --

26:35.500 --> 26:39.080
"Yester-me" can
come meet "now-me,"

26:39.080 --> 26:40.500
but "future-me"
can't go back.

26:40.500 --> 26:42.290
Okay,
now-me has a headache.

26:42.290 --> 26:44.290
[ Chuckles ]
Now-me wishes I could talk to
future-me about tonight.

26:44.290 --> 26:45.920
Clamp.

26:45.920 --> 26:47.040
What's happening tonight?

26:47.040 --> 26:48.880
Oh, uh, n-n--
Uh, nothing.

26:50.120 --> 26:51.210
Funny story.

26:51.210 --> 26:53.080
When I was little,
I used to wish

26:53.080 --> 26:55.330
I could go back in time
and meet my birth mother.

26:55.330 --> 26:57.750
-Not me.
-Really? Never?

26:57.750 --> 26:59.040
Well, you were
put up for adoption.

26:59.040 --> 27:00.540
I was left
outside a firehouse.

27:00.540 --> 27:02.540
-Fair enough.
-I'd meet your mom, though.

27:02.540 --> 27:04.170
Ellis Grey was
this world-renowned,

27:04.170 --> 27:06.710
award-winning surgeon and --
[ Gasps ]

27:06.710 --> 27:10.540
Wait. What if Cerone
was an Ellis stalker?

27:10.540 --> 27:13.080
Like -- Like -- Like a groupie,
like "Single White Female"?

27:13.080 --> 27:15.080
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
-Oh, no, no, no, no.

27:15.080 --> 27:16.580
There's blood
in her N.G. tube.

27:16.580 --> 27:17.750
She's actively bleeding.

27:17.750 --> 27:19.120
From where?
A ruptured vessel?

27:19.120 --> 27:22.290
Or an ulcer or varices.

27:22.290 --> 27:24.790
Oh, man.

27:24.790 --> 27:26.880
[ Sighs ]

27:26.880 --> 27:28.380
Okay, I'm gonna need to
scope her.

27:28.380 --> 27:31.460
Bring in the C-arm for an angio
and order 10 units!

27:31.460 --> 27:34.670
[ Beeping continues ]

27:41.500 --> 27:42.750
Richard:
Okay, the peritoneum is ready.

27:42.750 --> 27:45.330
[ Heart monitor beeping ]

27:45.330 --> 27:49.170
This tissue
looks perfect.

27:49.170 --> 27:52.080
Jackson: Need a six-oh
on a driver, please.

27:52.080 --> 27:53.540
That was beautiful work,
dear.

27:53.540 --> 27:55.210
Thank you.

27:55.210 --> 27:57.620
[ Beeping continues ]

28:00.290 --> 28:02.380
You know,
I really like her, Mom.

28:02.380 --> 28:03.620
I know.

28:03.620 --> 28:05.540
I like her, too.

28:05.540 --> 28:07.540
And I want it to work
between us.

28:09.670 --> 28:13.750
But if it does all go to hell
with me and Maggie,

28:13.750 --> 28:16.750
then you do have my blessing
to take her side.

28:16.750 --> 28:18.580
Deal?

28:20.880 --> 28:22.330
Deal.

28:22.330 --> 28:26.710
[ Air hissing ]

28:26.710 --> 28:29.420
[ Monitors beeping ]

28:29.420 --> 28:31.540
Maggie: So much bleeding.
I-I can't find the source.

28:31.540 --> 28:32.540
Okay, Bokhee, contrast.

28:34.040 --> 28:35.710
Good, good, good.

28:35.710 --> 28:38.170
Oh, where are you?
Where are you?

28:38.170 --> 28:40.170
I wish I could go back in time
to before this happened.

28:40.170 --> 28:42.250
-You can't go backwards --
-I know. I know.

28:42.250 --> 28:43.500
There it is. There it is.
See it?

28:43.500 --> 28:46.620
Ah, yes, I will
advance the catheter

28:46.620 --> 28:49.290
and try to
embolize the bleed.

28:49.290 --> 28:51.620
I think Cerone was
telling the truth about Ellis.

28:51.620 --> 28:52.830
We can't know for sure.

28:52.830 --> 28:54.120
There's proof.

28:54.120 --> 28:56.120
I'm the proof.

28:56.120 --> 28:57.540
Ellis didn't leave me
outside a firehouse,

28:57.540 --> 28:58.830
but she did
keep me a secret.

28:58.830 --> 29:00.790
She lied to Richard.
She lied to Meredith.

29:00.790 --> 29:02.170
If she's capable of
doing that

29:02.170 --> 29:03.830
to the people
she loves the most,

29:03.830 --> 29:06.290
you don't think she's capable of
screwing over a friend?

29:06.290 --> 29:07.580
[ Heart monitor beeping
rapidly ]

29:07.580 --> 29:09.250
Oh, damn it.

29:09.250 --> 29:11.420
Her B.P.'s
bottoming out.

29:11.420 --> 29:13.750
Okay, I can't
isolate this bleeder. Pierce?

29:13.750 --> 29:15.250
No, there is still
too much blood.

29:15.250 --> 29:16.790
Okay, Wilson,
you have to help me out here.

29:16.790 --> 29:18.710
Get in there
and open up her stomach.

29:18.710 --> 29:20.420
Okay. 10 blade.

29:20.420 --> 29:22.250
Come on, Marge.

29:24.830 --> 29:27.330
You want to
see the future.

29:27.330 --> 29:30.120
Help me understand your logic,
please.

29:30.120 --> 29:31.120
Owen,
our marriage is over.

29:31.120 --> 29:32.580
There's no point
in just hashing it --

29:32.580 --> 29:34.540
Amelia.

29:34.540 --> 29:37.080
Okay. Fine.

29:37.080 --> 29:39.500
You see this tumor?

29:39.500 --> 29:41.710
Officially, it's benign.

29:41.710 --> 29:43.620
No cancer.

29:43.620 --> 29:45.250
But if we leave it in, it's
gonna kill this kid, anyway.

29:45.250 --> 29:47.540
So, really, "benign"
is neither here nor there.

29:47.540 --> 29:49.210
-I don't how this is...
-Mm-hmm. Okay.

29:49.210 --> 29:51.670
So,
you were never with Teddy.

29:51.670 --> 29:53.580
You never played it out.
She was your friend.

29:53.580 --> 29:55.880
She was your person.

29:55.880 --> 29:57.380
Benign.

29:57.380 --> 30:00.460
But always there,
quietly growing.

30:00.460 --> 30:04.250
So, when you marry other women
and she's still there...

30:07.120 --> 30:09.000
She's not benign.

30:10.330 --> 30:12.670
[ Scoffs ]

30:12.670 --> 30:14.750
She rejected me.

30:14.750 --> 30:17.500
Because you were married,
dummy.

30:17.500 --> 30:20.040
And she's not as flawed
as we are.

30:20.040 --> 30:24.000
Wait. You are single now.
You're free.

30:24.000 --> 30:26.460
And you can't get it together
to tell her how you feel?

30:26.460 --> 30:28.500
What is stopping you?

30:28.500 --> 30:31.210
Well, I kind of feel like
all we talk about

30:31.210 --> 30:33.540
since our "no feelings" rule
is, uh, feelings.

30:33.540 --> 30:34.540
[ Chuckles ]

30:34.540 --> 30:36.040
[ Chuckles ]

30:36.040 --> 30:37.540
Maybe it started
when we were breaking up.

30:37.540 --> 30:38.830
Maybe that's why
I didn't notice.

30:38.830 --> 30:40.540
What?
The baby's dad.

30:40.540 --> 30:41.620
This baby's dad.

30:41.620 --> 30:43.420
Mike.

30:43.420 --> 30:45.040
We were gonna
get married.

30:45.040 --> 30:48.080
Noah was so happy
to have a dad.

30:48.080 --> 30:50.460
He was so excited
to be a big brother.

30:50.460 --> 30:55.000
But, uh, Mike would always
call Noah "your son"

30:55.000 --> 30:57.710
and this one "our baby,"

30:57.710 --> 31:00.580
like Noah was just
some piece of furniture

31:00.580 --> 31:02.380
that I moved
into his house.

31:02.380 --> 31:05.250
"Our baby will be
raised like this,"

31:05.250 --> 31:07.620
and, "Your son should know
better than that."

31:07.620 --> 31:09.960
I loved him.

31:09.960 --> 31:12.670
But I knew that if I stayed,

31:12.670 --> 31:15.880
I would have a husband,
but Noah would never have a dad.

31:15.880 --> 31:19.210
So I left him.

31:19.210 --> 31:22.710
And I cried every day
for months.

31:22.710 --> 31:28.790
[ Voice breaking ] And maybe
that's why I didn't notice...

31:28.790 --> 31:31.120
when Noah's laugh
changed.

31:33.170 --> 31:37.670
Liz --
I just want to go back
and notice.

31:37.670 --> 31:39.670
[ Crying ]

31:41.670 --> 31:43.540
Oh, God.

31:43.540 --> 31:46.620
Dahlia: Checked back for wound,
placed pelvic binder,

31:46.620 --> 31:49.880
transfused two units, and ruled
out intra-abdominal bleeding.

31:49.880 --> 31:51.210
She should be stable now.
Nice work, guys.

31:52.710 --> 31:54.040
I'm back! I'm here!

31:54.040 --> 31:55.500
[ All sighing, murmuring ]

31:55.500 --> 31:57.920
Dr. Kepner, our patient with
the facial trauma survived.

31:57.920 --> 31:59.120
How do you know that?

31:59.120 --> 32:00.920
Casey: Oh,
we tried nasal intubation,

32:00.920 --> 32:03.080
but that was impossible in
the...weather conditions,

32:03.080 --> 32:04.920
so we criked him,
and it worked.

32:04.920 --> 32:05.710
We established an airway.

32:05.710 --> 32:06.830
April: Who says?

32:06.830 --> 32:08.210
Um...I say?

32:11.790 --> 32:13.620
[ Sighs ] All right,
well, I guess I'll
have to give it to you

32:13.620 --> 32:14.960
since I was just paged
on a freaking goose chase.

32:14.960 --> 32:17.120
No fair.
He's the one who paged you.

32:18.420 --> 32:21.290
What?

32:21.290 --> 32:22.460
I realized
that the thing that

32:22.460 --> 32:24.210
was most endangering
our patients was you.

32:24.210 --> 32:26.540
I figured, if I took you
out of the equation,

32:26.540 --> 32:28.330
I neutralized the threat.

32:28.330 --> 32:31.120
[ Laughs ]

32:31.120 --> 32:34.040
You tried to
cheat the system.

32:34.040 --> 32:35.790
DeLuca:
No offense, Dr. Kepner,

32:35.790 --> 32:37.170
but you did something similar
in your Cert.

32:37.170 --> 32:39.290
The ambulance story
is legendary.

32:39.290 --> 32:40.790
No, I mean, I-I know.
That's why it's funny --

32:40.790 --> 32:42.460
because -- because
three months after

32:42.460 --> 32:43.920
I cheated
to get my Trauma Cert,

32:43.920 --> 32:45.790
a car-crash victim
came in to this E.R.,

32:45.790 --> 32:47.250
and guess what.

32:47.250 --> 32:50.420
I-I couldn't save him.
[ Laughs ]

32:50.420 --> 32:53.250
Oh, my God.

32:53.250 --> 32:55.420
He died right in front of me.
[ Laughs ]

32:55.420 --> 32:56.920
Dr. Kepner, do we need to
pause the exercise?

32:56.920 --> 32:58.580
No, no, no, no, no,
you can't pause

32:58.580 --> 33:01.460
because in real life,
the trauma doesn't just stop!

33:01.460 --> 33:03.380
God doesn't work that way.

33:03.380 --> 33:05.830
Because you can do
every single thing right,

33:05.830 --> 33:07.830
and still, people die.

33:07.830 --> 33:09.210
Like, look, look.

33:09.210 --> 33:10.620
This guy right here --
this guy --

33:10.620 --> 33:13.460
he was just, you know,
living his life, right?

33:13.460 --> 33:15.290
He was applying to colleges,
and then one day --

33:15.290 --> 33:17.750
bam! --
shot in the neck.

33:17.750 --> 33:22.000
And then he's dead because,
guys, there are no rules.

33:22.000 --> 33:23.290
Okay, Dr. Kepner,
I-I-I think that's enough.

33:23.290 --> 33:25.040
And this?
This woman --

33:25.040 --> 33:26.830
This woman was about
to become a mom.

33:26.830 --> 33:29.080
Her husband was so happy.

33:29.080 --> 33:31.120
They both were.
And one second, she was fine,

33:31.120 --> 33:33.830
and then the next,
we couldn't...

33:33.830 --> 33:35.420
[ Exhales heavily ]

33:35.420 --> 33:37.880
We couldn't save her.

33:37.880 --> 33:39.170
We couldn't save her.

33:39.170 --> 33:41.120
We couldn't...
[ Siren wailing ]

33:43.710 --> 33:45.670
Come on. Come on.

33:45.670 --> 33:47.000
Come on! Come on!

33:47.000 --> 33:48.750
Dr. Kepner, Dr. Kepner.

33:48.750 --> 33:50.540
Hey.

33:50.540 --> 33:52.210
Are you okay?

33:56.920 --> 33:58.620
We're do-- We're done.

33:58.620 --> 34:00.170
We're done.

34:00.170 --> 34:07.120
♪♪

34:07.120 --> 34:14.040
♪♪

34:20.460 --> 34:23.210
-Sorry.
-[ Sighs ]

34:23.210 --> 34:26.120
She was a woman
before her time.

34:26.120 --> 34:28.830
She was
bat-crap crazy.

34:28.830 --> 34:31.540
And she was a genius.

34:31.540 --> 34:35.210
It's a thin line
the real trailblazers straddle.

34:35.210 --> 34:38.290
[ Sighs ]
And who knows?

34:38.290 --> 34:40.790
Ol' Bargin' Marge
might've done it one day,

34:40.790 --> 34:42.620
discovered time travel.

34:42.620 --> 34:45.080
An engineer decided to walk

34:45.080 --> 34:47.380
in front of
a radar magnetron one day,

34:47.380 --> 34:49.290
melted the candy bar
in his pocket,

34:49.290 --> 34:51.170
and discovered
the microwave.

34:51.170 --> 34:52.580
People thought he was crazy

34:52.580 --> 34:56.210
for suggesting
they use it to heat food.

34:56.210 --> 35:00.080
No, at the very least,
she pushed back.

35:00.080 --> 35:04.420
She took the first step,
and she said, "Maybe."

35:04.420 --> 35:09.000
Maybe you should name your
device "the Bargin' Marge."

35:09.000 --> 35:11.040
Now, that would be
disrespectful.

35:11.040 --> 35:12.540
It goes in people's rectums,
Wilson.

35:12.540 --> 35:14.380
Right. Sorry.

35:15.960 --> 35:17.750
"The Trailblazer."

35:17.750 --> 35:21.040
Perfect.

35:21.040 --> 35:25.540
♪ I see our footprints
in the sand ♪

35:25.540 --> 35:29.620
♪ I feel hairs raise
on the back of my hand ♪

35:29.620 --> 35:33.420
♪ Take me northbound,
back to home ♪

35:33.420 --> 35:36.210
♪ Where I know ♪

35:36.210 --> 35:40.210
♪ You feel like you're alone ♪

35:40.210 --> 35:41.330
♪ And you feel like
something's wrong ♪

35:41.330 --> 35:43.250
Hey.

35:43.250 --> 35:46.710
♪ I feel like I won't know ♪

35:46.710 --> 35:48.170
Hey. You all right?

35:48.170 --> 35:50.420
-No, I --
-April, hold on. Hold on.

35:50.420 --> 35:51.830
♪♪

35:51.830 --> 35:53.580
Let me -- Come here
for a second.

35:53.580 --> 35:58.920
♪ So keep me in mind ♪

35:58.920 --> 36:02.000
-What?
-What is going on?

36:02.000 --> 36:04.710
♪ Keep me in mind ♪
April.

36:04.710 --> 36:07.460
April, every time I see you, you
look like you're spinning out.

36:07.460 --> 36:09.210
Ohh...
Okay? Every time
I try to talk to you,

36:09.210 --> 36:10.920
you slam the door in my face.
-I'm...

36:10.920 --> 36:12.540
♪ Keep me in mind ♪
When? Huh?

36:12.540 --> 36:14.120
When did you decide that
we're not friends anymore,

36:14.120 --> 36:15.330
that you can't talk to me?

36:15.330 --> 36:19.170
When did you decide that...
I'm not here for you?

36:21.380 --> 36:23.330
[ Sighs ]

36:28.670 --> 36:31.330
[ Sighs ]

36:31.330 --> 36:32.750
I'm sorry.

36:32.750 --> 36:34.170
What can I do?

36:38.330 --> 36:39.460
Oh.

36:39.460 --> 36:41.460
Whoa, April.

36:41.460 --> 36:43.080
April, no, no, no.

36:43.080 --> 36:44.500
You said
you wanted to help.

36:44.500 --> 36:47.750
April, look, you can't fix
what you can't face, all right?

36:47.750 --> 36:49.080
Please.
-Fine!

36:49.080 --> 36:51.250
Just talk to me.

36:53.250 --> 36:56.000
Can you take Harriet tonight?
That would really help.

36:56.000 --> 36:58.750
Thanks.

36:58.750 --> 37:00.960
[ Door slams ]

37:04.290 --> 37:05.460
You're being a wormhole.

37:05.460 --> 37:06.880
What?

37:06.880 --> 37:08.880
You're being a wormhole
for your mother.

37:08.880 --> 37:10.380
What are you
talking about?

37:10.380 --> 37:12.540
Ellis did something
30 years ago,

37:12.540 --> 37:14.710
and it's messing with
everything we've built today

37:14.710 --> 37:16.880
because you're letting it.
-Jo, you didn't know my mother,

37:16.880 --> 37:18.460
but she doesn't need my help
to mess with me.

37:18.460 --> 37:19.830
Yes, she does.

37:19.830 --> 37:23.040
She does because she's gone
and you're still here.

37:23.040 --> 37:26.080
Your mother was a trailblazer,
Meredith.

37:26.080 --> 37:27.790
If she was here, she wouldn't
want you to sit back

37:27.790 --> 37:29.330
and polish her legacy.

37:29.330 --> 37:31.500
She would want you to try
the crazy thing.

37:31.500 --> 37:33.580
She would want you to
try everything.

37:33.580 --> 37:35.210
-[ Sighs ]
-I'm saying,

37:35.210 --> 37:37.250
don't let something that
your mother did in the past

37:37.250 --> 37:39.620
wipe out your chance
to change the future.

37:43.330 --> 37:44.670
Okay.

37:44.670 --> 37:45.830
"Okay," what?

37:49.620 --> 37:51.080
[ Papers rustling ]

37:57.330 --> 37:58.920
Let's get to work.

37:58.920 --> 38:01.040
Really?

38:01.040 --> 38:02.580
You called me a wormhole.

38:02.580 --> 38:04.920
[ Chuckles ] I did. I'm sorry.
Should I be sorry?

38:04.920 --> 38:06.500
Let's just get to work.

38:08.040 --> 38:09.830
Okay, this is, uh...

38:09.830 --> 38:12.170
[ Clears throat ]

38:12.170 --> 38:14.170
[ Door opens ]

38:14.170 --> 38:15.500
Hey. Oh, sorry.

38:15.500 --> 38:17.000
Oh.

38:17.000 --> 38:19.080
Oh, hey, how did it go today
with your mom and Richard?

38:19.080 --> 38:20.460
Were they awful?

38:20.460 --> 38:22.250
They were great.
I mean, eventually.

38:22.250 --> 38:25.170
Oh. Wow. Okay.

38:25.170 --> 38:28.120
Obstacle number one...
not such an obstacle.

38:28.120 --> 38:31.710
-Mm.
-So, you ready for dinner?

38:31.710 --> 38:33.960
-Um...
-Oh. You have company.

38:33.960 --> 38:35.330
I do, yeah.

38:35.330 --> 38:37.670
Uh, April is, uh --
Sorry.

38:37.670 --> 38:39.500
Oh, no, no.
No. I get it.

38:39.500 --> 38:42.120
Yeah, no, she's just going
through something big, so...

38:42.120 --> 38:43.540
Well, no.
We have plenty of time.

38:43.540 --> 38:47.080
You know,
the longer we wait to eat...

38:48.710 --> 38:50.250
The hungrier you'll be.

39:02.540 --> 39:05.830
[ Sighs ]

39:05.830 --> 39:08.380
[ Noah laughing ]

39:08.380 --> 39:10.540
I-It's inoperable?

39:10.540 --> 39:12.750
It's too close
to his brainstem.

39:12.750 --> 39:14.330
I can't get to it
with a scalpel.

39:14.330 --> 39:17.170
But this project
that we're working on --

39:17.170 --> 39:20.210
the ultrasound --
he could be a candidate.

39:20.210 --> 39:21.880
I thought that you hadn't
done human trials.

39:21.880 --> 39:23.960
We don't --
We haven't yet.

39:23.960 --> 39:26.290
I barely kept a 23-week-old baby
in her today,

39:26.290 --> 39:28.040
and you want me to go in there
and ask her

39:28.040 --> 39:29.750
if her 8-year-old
can be your guinea pig?

39:29.750 --> 39:31.460
I'm sorry.
That's your plan?!

39:31.460 --> 39:33.210
We don't have any other
course of treatment.

39:33.210 --> 39:34.750
And he's seizing
every three minutes.

39:34.750 --> 39:36.080
This is his only shot.

39:36.080 --> 39:38.790
[ Sleeping At Last's "Three"
plays ]

39:38.790 --> 39:40.540
Do you want to come in with us
to talk to her?

39:40.540 --> 39:42.380
No!

39:42.380 --> 39:44.580
No.

39:44.580 --> 39:46.790
Damn it.

39:46.790 --> 39:50.540
♪ Maybe I've done enough ♪

39:50.540 --> 39:53.040
[ Noah laughing ]

39:53.040 --> 39:56.880
♪ And your golden child
grew up ♪

39:56.880 --> 40:02.330
♪ Maybe this trophy
isn't real love ♪
Yeah, okay.

40:02.330 --> 40:04.040
Meredith: When the worst
of our fears are realized...

40:04.040 --> 40:06.290
♪ And with or without it ♪

40:06.290 --> 40:08.960
Hi.
♪ I'm good enough ♪

40:08.960 --> 40:10.040
[ Laughing ]

40:10.040 --> 40:12.040
[ Chuckles ]

40:12.040 --> 40:15.670
♪ Maybe I've done enough ♪

40:15.670 --> 40:18.120
♪♪

40:18.120 --> 40:22.830
♪ Finally catching up ♪

40:22.830 --> 40:30.210
♪ For the first time I see
an image of my brokenness ♪

40:30.210 --> 40:34.040
♪ Utterly worthy of love ♪

40:34.040 --> 40:36.170
[ Dummy clatters ]

40:36.170 --> 40:41.540
♪ Maybe I've done enough ♪

40:41.540 --> 40:47.290
[ Crying ]

40:47.290 --> 40:50.580
...when everything we've
counted on has disappeared...

40:50.580 --> 40:54.500
♪ And I finally see myself ♪

40:54.500 --> 40:58.710
♪♪

40:58.710 --> 41:01.580
...something still drives us
to try to fix the past...

41:01.580 --> 41:03.460
♪♪

41:03.460 --> 41:05.920
Airport.
International terminal, please.

41:05.920 --> 41:07.330
♪♪

41:07.330 --> 41:10.830
...or to find our future...

41:10.830 --> 41:13.880
Okay. Come on.

41:13.880 --> 41:16.460
♪ Now I only want what's real ♪

41:16.460 --> 41:18.330
All right.

41:18.330 --> 41:20.040
You good?

41:20.040 --> 41:21.710
Mm-hmm.
♪ To let my heart feel
what it feels ♪

41:21.710 --> 41:22.790
...when the only thing that
really needs our attention

41:22.790 --> 41:24.040
is the present...

41:24.040 --> 41:25.500
[ Sighs ]

41:25.500 --> 41:26.960
♪ Gold, silver, or bronze ♪

41:26.960 --> 41:28.500
-Mommy?
-Hmm?

41:28.500 --> 41:30.380
♪ Hold no value here ♪

41:30.380 --> 41:33.580
Are you crying because
Noah has a tumor?

41:33.580 --> 41:35.170
No. No.

41:35.170 --> 41:36.790
Um...

41:36.790 --> 41:38.960
No, I'm crying
'cause I'm lucky.

41:38.960 --> 41:41.880
I am so lucky

41:41.880 --> 41:46.710
to have a beautiful, smart,
healthy little girl.

41:46.710 --> 41:48.170
♪ I set aside
the highlight reel ♪

41:48.170 --> 41:51.540
And sometimes I get so busy
that I forget how lucky I am.

41:51.540 --> 41:55.040
♪ And leave my greatest failures
on display ♪

41:55.040 --> 41:57.170
You know what?

41:57.170 --> 41:59.290
How about tomorrow
I take the day off?

41:59.290 --> 42:00.920
♪ With an asterisk ♪

42:00.920 --> 42:02.670
You and I can go
find an adventure,

42:02.670 --> 42:04.960
just the two of us, okay?

42:04.960 --> 42:06.330
Yeah?
♪ Worthy of love anyway ♪

42:06.330 --> 42:07.920
Yeah? Yeah?
[ Laughs ]

42:07.920 --> 42:10.750
...and its infinite
possibilities.

42:10.750 --> 42:12.710
Ooh, I love you.

42:12.710 --> 42:14.670
All right, sweet dreams.

42:27.540 --> 42:33.620
♪♪

42:33.620 --> 42:39.920
♪♪

42:39.920 --> 42:46.290
♪♪

42:46.290 --> 42:52.380
♪♪
